data.content:
**No Thread.Abort migration is needed here.**

Your code only uses `Thread.Start`, `Thread.Join`, and `Thread.Sleep` — none of which are affected by the .NET Framework → .NET 8 migration. These APIs work identically in modern .NET. There are no calls to `Thread.Abort`, no `ThreadAbortException` catch blocks, no `Thread.ResetAbort`, and no `Thread.Interrupt`. The code will compile and run correctly as-is on .NET 8.

**Optional modernization (unrelated to Thread.Abort):** You could replace the manual thread management with `Parallel.ForEach` or `Task.Run` for cleaner code, e.g.:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public void RunBatch(List<WorkItem> items)
    {
        Parallel.ForEach(items, item => Process(item));
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item)
    {
        Thread.Sleep(100);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

But this is purely an improvement — your existing code requires zero changes for the migration.
